[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":359},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-13-types-and-javascript\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-13-types-and-javascript\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-13-types-and-javascript\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-13-types-and-javascript\u002F":335,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-13-types-and-javascript\u002F":344},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190516\u002F3276239225\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":318,"date":319,"description":320,"extension":321,"lang":322,"meta":323,"navigation":324,"path":325,"readingMinutes":326,"seo":327,"standalone":328,"stem":329,"tags":330,"tldr":332,"updated":319,"url":333,"__hash__":334},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjsweirdworld-13-types-and-javascript.md","[JS Weird World] No.13 Quick Concept Check — Types and JavaScript","1000031679",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":312},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,30,33,97,104,192,198,201,221,224,252,259,264,271,275,278,295,299,308],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"This kicks off a brand-new chapter: \"Types and Operators.\"",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"dynamic-typing","Dynamic typing",[17,25,26],{},[27,28],"img",{"alt":23,"src":29},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FzrSAdDnh.png",[17,31,32],{},"Dynamic typing basically means you don't have to rush to tell JavaScript what type your variable is — JavaScript figures it out for you. Pretty neat, right? I won't get into how other languages do it (the course touches on that a bit), I'll just focus on how JavaScript handles it. So let's look at some example code to get a feel for it.",[34,35,40],"pre",{"className":36,"code":37,"language":38,"meta":39,"style":39},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var a = 1234;\nvar b = '1234';\nvar c = true;\n","js","",[41,42,43,66,82],"code",{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,45,48,52,56,59,63],"span",{"class":46,"line":47},"line",1,[44,49,51],{"class":50},"sWyjQ","var",[44,53,55],{"class":54},"sMAXC"," a ",[44,57,58],{"class":50},"=",[44,60,62],{"class":61},"sCcAr"," 1234",[44,64,65],{"class":54},";\n",[44,67,69,71,74,76,80],{"class":46,"line":68},2,[44,70,51],{"class":50},[44,72,73],{"class":54}," b ",[44,75,58],{"class":50},[44,77,79],{"class":78},"sTRMh"," '1234'",[44,81,65],{"class":54},[44,83,85,87,90,92,95],{"class":46,"line":84},3,[44,86,51],{"class":50},[44,88,89],{"class":54}," c ",[44,91,58],{"class":50},[44,93,94],{"class":61}," true",[44,96,65],{"class":54},[17,98,99,100,103],{},"Honestly, from that example alone it's hard to tell how JavaScript identifies the variable types. So let me add one more piece of syntax to help us out — ",[41,101,102],{},"typeof()",".",[34,105,107],{"className":36,"code":106,"language":38,"meta":39,"style":39},"var a = 1234;\nvar b = '1234';\nvar c = true;\nconsole.log(typeof(a));\nconsole.log(typeof(b));\nconsole.log(typeof(c));\n",[41,108,109,121,133,145,164,178],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,110,111,113,115,117,119],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,112,51],{"class":50},[44,114,55],{"class":54},[44,116,58],{"class":50},[44,118,62],{"class":61},[44,120,65],{"class":54},[44,122,123,125,127,129,131],{"class":46,"line":68},[44,124,51],{"class":50},[44,126,73],{"class":54},[44,128,58],{"class":50},[44,130,79],{"class":78},[44,132,65],{"class":54},[44,134,135,137,139,141,143],{"class":46,"line":84},[44,136,51],{"class":50},[44,138,89],{"class":54},[44,140,58],{"class":50},[44,142,94],{"class":61},[44,144,65],{"class":54},[44,146,148,151,155,158,161],{"class":46,"line":147},4,[44,149,150],{"class":54},"console.",[44,152,154],{"class":153},"sj_SG","log",[44,156,157],{"class":54},"(",[44,159,160],{"class":50},"typeof",[44,162,163],{"class":54},"(a));\n",[44,165,167,169,171,173,175],{"class":46,"line":166},5,[44,168,150],{"class":54},[44,170,154],{"class":153},[44,172,157],{"class":54},[44,174,160],{"class":50},[44,176,177],{"class":54},"(b));\n",[44,179,181,183,185,187,189],{"class":46,"line":180},6,[44,182,150],{"class":54},[44,184,154],{"class":153},[44,186,157],{"class":54},[44,188,160],{"class":50},[44,190,191],{"class":54},"(c));\n",[17,193,194],{},[27,195],{"alt":196,"src":197},"Types","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FwzRsz2Eh.png",[17,199,200],{},"Isn't it surprising that JavaScript just identifies the variable types for us? So how does it do that?",[202,203,204,208,211],"ul",{},[205,206,207],"li",{},"Strings wrapped in single or double quotes all get treated as String.",[205,209,210],{},"Numbers don't need quotes — a number is identified as Number directly.",[205,212,213,214,217,218,103],{},"Booleans need no explanation: ",[41,215,216],{},"true"," and ",[41,219,220],{},"false",[17,222,223],{},"The one thing to watch out for: a string always needs single or double quotes. If you don't wrap it and just write this:",[34,225,227],{"className":36,"code":226,"language":38,"meta":39,"style":39},"var a = hellow;\nconsole.log(typeof(a));\n",[41,228,229,240],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,230,231,233,235,237],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,232,51],{"class":50},[44,234,55],{"class":54},[44,236,58],{"class":50},[44,238,239],{"class":54}," hellow;\n",[44,241,242,244,246,248,250],{"class":46,"line":68},[44,243,150],{"class":54},[44,245,154],{"class":153},[44,247,157],{"class":54},[44,249,160],{"class":50},[44,251,163],{"class":54},[17,253,254,255,258],{},"You'll definitely get a ",[41,256,257],{},"not defined"," back.",[17,260,261],{},[27,262],{"alt":257,"src":263},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FsgowzxPh.png",[17,265,266,267,270],{},"Why? Because JavaScript mistakes ",[41,268,269],{},"hellow"," for a variable.",[12,272,274],{"id":273},"static-typing","Static typing",[17,276,277],{},"Let me also quickly explain static typing. In some other languages, when you create a variable you have to declare its type. Like this (the example below is C#):",[34,279,283],{"className":280,"code":281,"language":282,"meta":39,"style":39},"language-c# shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","int i = 123;\nstring say = \"Hello\";\n","c#",[41,284,285,290],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,286,287],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,288,289],{},"int i = 123;\n",[44,291,292],{"class":46,"line":68},[44,293,294],{},"string say = \"Hello\";\n",[12,296,298],{"id":297},"image-source","Image source",[17,300,301],{},[302,303,307],"a",{"href":304,"rel":305},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.udemy.com\u002Fjavascriptjs\u002F",[306],"nofollow","JavaScript Full Guide: Conquering the Weird Parts of JS",[309,310,311],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}",{"title":39,"searchDepth":68,"depth":68,"links":313},[314,315,316,317],{"id":14,"depth":68,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":68,"text":23},{"id":273,"depth":68,"text":274},{"id":297,"depth":68,"text":298},"JsWeirdWorld","2019-05-16 19:00:35","This kicks off a brand-new chapter: \"Types and Operators.\" We start with how JavaScript handles types — dynamic typing, where you don't have to tell JS what type a variable is because it figures that 